text: Could one have made a movie of this type without attaching it to a brand name? A younger generation interacting with the older one, gamers going into the game, a regurgitation of tropes. Nothing new will come out of this movie, there will be some funny lines and exciting scenes, but it will all play out as expected and there will be no surprises, it will only make us for 90 minutes numb to whatever pain is going on outside the cinema or in our dull brains. The only pain i can expect is being forced to watch a committee-made movie designed to elicit a response which has already surpassed its purposes, to realise this is a movie (like so many from hollywood) made solely to earn a profit for the machine - however, being fed the earnest respect and love for the original film and the material its based on, the unique cast and their rapport will serve some as well intentioned, I'll try to be convinced this is new entertainment for a new generation. The movie might bomb at the box office (how did this happen?) or it might succeed financially (good news for fans of Jumanji 2), but who really cares if there is a lack of total creative exploration in the most influential art known to the planet?

text: From the first trailer, I think it's a rental. What made the first Jumanji so great was there was a sense of danger to it because there was no avatar. The original had an excitement of "survive, win or die," but also managed to keep it fun. The avatar aspect of this "Jumanji" doesn't give you that feeling: it takes away from that. I mean Jack Black just was eaten by a hippo and I bet nothing happens to him. Like Robin Williams says in the first one, "Jumanji has consequences." Also if you consider your movie a "sequel," how is the magic of the board transferred into a video game, just use the ancient magical board.

text: This looks far better than I was expecting from the scant details so far. I like messing with characters by forcing them into other stereotypes. I'm not saying this is going to be a great or amazing movie, just that it doesn't look like the complete loss I feared. Looks like it will be a fun popcorn flick.  The major difference I see is that in the original, part of the intensity was that the game invaded your world. Altered what was familiar and safe for the player and made it dangerous and unknown. That really amped up the danger and sense of impending doom. With this, they are pulled into the world and they know it is a video game. I'm wondering if the filmmakers will be able to convey the same sense of real danger. Or actually, if that even matters to the film at all.  Regardless, this looks fun, and Karen Gilan is turning into quite the action actress. I'm okay with that.

text: Now, people are all "where is the board game"? I get that. But I'm sure the original also had people wondering, "huh? All that fuss over a board game?". I loved the originals, don't get me wrong, and I really just want this remake to be good. One of my main worries is that from this trailer, I feel it may be missing the emotional sincerity that the original had, the depth and dare to be 'cheesy' and still pull it off. Perhaps that was a by product of the times and type of direction of the original, or maybe they're just hiding that in this trailer so as to not give it all away. Either way, I like the cast and the fact that it's Jumanji, so I'll give it a shot and hope they manage to pack the same punch the original gave.

text: It looks okay if I'm being honest, what I find wrong is that it lost its Jumangi feel to it, the original one had this essence of wonder, adventure and the thrill of what would happen, this just looks like a mashup of King King and Temple Run. I dont like that it has the name Jumangi attached to the title because it really not similar, its more like a spiritual sequel like Zathura, even that movie was more similar to the original. Another thing I dont like is that like the original and Zathura, the main cast consisted of children/teens and it seemed to work better that way, I dont like that Hollywood decided to put grown adults as the main cast as it totally ruined the essence of the Jumangi game. With children you could think "what will their next move be?" like Home Alone kind of, but with an adult cast that thought in me will be lost (even though I know they are just avatars of the kids, its not the same to me). I will still watch it to see if I still feel the same way but I will wait for it to become available on Red Box.

text: I like the original concept better. one of the characters came back spending all his youth stuck in Jumanji, his friends were traumatized by it, the movie had great comedic moments it also had realistic adult themes that actually made jumanji seem like a scary game i wouldn't want to play. I also liked the exaggerated versions of African wildlife running rampant in city setting. You literally had a house with a monsoon going on inside it and a floor comparable to quick sand.    It's cool Jumanji is a video game now but really it just feels like a body swap movie that takes place in the jungle. If this was the first Jumanji movie and the original was the sequel, I would see that as a step up. this concept just seems way more dumbed down than the original to me.

text: Nobody would have complained if it was a Jumanji sequel done right. Nobody would have complained if it was a frame by frame remake with modern technology. The issue lies with the fact it takes away all the aspects of the original. Most notably tone. Even with all the changes made, this could have been a salvageable plot of going into the game. But you can't turn it into a Kevin Hart/Jack Black comedy.   What we're gonna get is Kevin Hart short jokes and about a dozen "Ew Elephant Poop! Haha!" comedy. Also most notably. Why is it a video game? If it was because "video games are more popular" that's just stupid cause it's still an Atari they find, not a PS4. And while people still play Board games regularly...people don't play Atari. Also let's also note the game's menu screen has modern HD graphics yet it's on an Atari.   The premise can still work with them getting sucked into the board game...so there is literally no reason to make it a video game. I wanted to like this movie. The teaser yesterday was promising but this was every fear I had ever since its announcement.

text: To be fair, the movie looks like it has potential. People getting angry have their nostalgia goggles strapped tightly to their faces. But here's the thing: of COURSE they will. Because this is not only a remake of an 80's movie, but it is a remake of arguably the second-best Robin Williams movie there is. And they completely removed anything remotely Jumanji except for "jungle game".  A remake should take the original material in a new direction. Maybe Allen could have to deal with PTSD caused by 30 years in the jungle. Maybe the children need surprisingly little help due to the current technological advancements. But do NOT deviate THIS far and call it Jumanji.  If they had made this its own thing, it might be even better. Heck, they could've played with the video game aspect cleverly. But they just never learn: trying to tie this to a previous movie that people love could only serve to doom this movie.
author: Jaedon Braun

text: The only reason this movie is getting as much backlash as it is is because it has the name Jumanji attached to it. If it was just another action and CGI filmed comedy, no one would be complaining too much. Yeah it has  its fair share of cliches and the trailer doesn't do much to separate it from most blockbusters nowadays, but it doesn't look horrendous. Having the actors portray characters that are very different from who they are personally is an interesting fish-out-of-water concept and can lead to some funny results. It won't be fantastic but it will be passable.   SO DON'T COMPARE THIS TO THE ORIGINAL JUMANJI! It's not trying to be the original and it's not a remake of the original it's just borrowing it's concept. Don't be butthurt because this is "ruining your childhood". They are only Using Jumanji's name to get more attention and money  Sidenote: Jumanji was a book by Chris Van Allsburg. It wasn't Robin William's brain-child. So if you're going to say it's a disgrace to anyone, make it a disgrace to Chris
author: Christopher Reistle

text: Had high hopes for the movie. I originally believed that the idea would have been to have the board game we all recognised from the original film, and the characters would have been sucked into it like Robin Williams' character, thus we would get to experience what life INSIDE the game would have been like - answering the question we had years ago. But instead, they've done a Ghostbusters 2016 and have completely smashed up any form of continuity. I'm aware that it's a remake, but still seriously, a video game? Jumanji's name is famous for the board game platform, it's what made Jumanji an iconic idea. I'll give the film a chance when it comes out, but I don't have any decent expectations.

text: So many mixed emotions. Love Dwayne, Jack & Kevin. Miss Robin terribly. Sort of like that they flipped the script so the characters go into the gaming world instead of the game hazards coming out of the game. Hate that its been converted into a video game. Like the music ... some of GnR's best. Still really really hate that they're tying this Tron meets Scott Pilgrim -VS- The World meets the final season of Charmed where they "glamoured" themselves to hide their identities to the legacy that is Jumanji. Just because they were sucked into the jungle environment of a game doesn't make it Jumanji. I'd probably like it if it had a new, unique name all its own but they've tainted it for me reminding me that there will never be another Robin Williams movie and even trying to come close to carrying on that storyline without him. What's next? .... Night At The Museum: Quantum Leaps where the security guard is transported through a time machine into history to change the outcomes of certain historic events, thereby changing the artifacts displayed in the museum???? *eyeroll*

text: For me I'm trying hard to see something positive in this.  Here's my view. 1. They take it from a board game to a video game, possibly something akin to WOW.      I can see why they did this, as how many kids actually play board games these days? 2. Children become their in game avatars - again I can see the reasoning.  While I know some guys like playing as a hot chick, I'm not sure if the girls do this in reverse - but what the heck - we get Jack Black so who's complaining. 3. For me the original was as much about Alan and Sarah as it was about the children, there's nothing in the trailer to suggest that element in this film, of course the trailer s cut from all the action pieces that they hope will get people to go and watch the film, so there may be things we're missing here.  To me this looks like something that's not going to be enjoyable.  Hollywood seems to have forgotten how to make a decent film that includes - a story - and seems content to just trot out the same action orientated rubbish time and time again.  Enough already.

text: I think that the best way to view this is to not expect Jumanji. Classic things are being rebooted left and right, and sure, of course it won't capture the charm of the original. But The Rock is the GOAT and Kevin Hart is hilarious, and regardless of nostalgia, it does look like it has a lot of entertainment value. I am looking for some good writing for the comedy, and good cinematography for the action scenes for this to be a real home run. The main reason why I am being lenient is because I am not expecting it to be faithful to the original because of three reasons:  1. It needs to be either 100% modern or 100% classic, no half assed in the middle  2. I haven't seen Jumanji in years and I can barely remember it. TBH, I didn't even know that Robin Williams was in it, that's how long it's been. I feel like lots of people are in the same boat as me, yet will still see the movie anyway  3. A video game is much different than a board game, so incorporating the dice rolls and element of surprise will make it feel much different.

text: Aaaand it's not a board game. Dead on arrival.  See, a board game that starts affecting the world around you as you play it is a neat idea. Especially when it sucking you into it is a special 'challenge' or something. But a video game that sucks you into it automatically? Do you know how many fucking times that's been done? This is just a jungle themed Tron.  And that's not getting into how generic the characters are. Just another garbage reboot. Do you know what would have at least been a better idea? They play the game on their phone - like the phone version of the Monopoly game or something - so you can at least still please whatever idiot exec that insisted that kids don't like board games anymore and it's gotta be a video game, while also still retaining everything that defines the Jumanji franchise. You at least gotta have the board game, the dice rolling and mysterious description of the upcoming event, and have the game affect real life. Getting sucked into Jumanji isn't what was memorable about the original, it was that Jumanji took over reality. The game came to life more and more with each dice roll.

text: I want to try and be impartial... but whoever thought we need a re imaging of Jumanji needs to have there head examined. Turning the board game into a video game is one of the worst ideas ever. Almost every attempt to make a video game movie has met with failure. Assassin Creed cough cough.   Also, where is the scary aspect from the original? A board game that spits out animals and other creatures, like the plant monsters from the original Jumanji. Those events gave you the sense of a horror movie aspect, (sucked into a board game / the hunter) while Robin Williams comedy lighted the mood. I'm not seeing that dynamic here at all and unless the characters from the new film have something especially new to offer. No one is going to bother with this obvious rip off.

text: The original Jumanji was about facing fear and growing up. The board game serves as a gateway to a mysterious jungle which is a metaphor for adulthood. The original movie was very good at conveying the fear the Robin Willliams character feels for adulthood through the archaic trappings of an ornate board game that looks like a relic from an older time; this also deepened the mystery that hooks the viewer. That fear is echoed in the younger 90s male character for whom Robin Williams serves as guide. The movie was also good at framing the journey into maturation as an adventure about the intrusion of the unknown into the familiar; closure came through the deepened understanding of the borders between the worlds of adulthood and childhood, and eventually enabled the characters to close the gateways to fear. The only gripe about that movie that I would have liked to see addressed in a sequel/reboot or whatever is the development of the female characters. I won't watch this, but I don't hold it against anyone who does. I just hope that at some point someone really does a sequel to Jumanji that expands on what was good about the original. Enjoy, you guys!

text: It feels like this has lost what makes the original great, which is the creepy mystery of what the game might unleash next. This looks like a group of celebrities romping through the forest as stock characters they've been before, grasping for some form of comedic dialogue.  What matters in Jumanji is that the game is REALLY effecting the world around the characters, and we care so much about Alan Parrish's story because he himself ACTUALLY gets sucked into a jungle for several years, a jungle that then begins forcing itself upon his hometown while expressing poetic riddles.  If even a hippopotamus attack is played for "laughs" in this Gun N' Roses adaptation, there seems to be no true danger or suspense.  The original puts us on the edge of our seats even as each stone carved piece ...somehow!?.. moves across the board. Why should we care about video game avatars when the characters don't seem to?  So MUCH can still be done with the board game to make it fresh and powerful in different ways. I would say that I'm going to miss the evocative power of a spooky game that lures people into digging itself up with an ethereal drum circle's heart beat, but I'll probably just watch the 1995 award winning hit Jumanji and skip whatever this is supposed to be.

text: I remember seeing the original in the theater as a kid (around ten). I found it to be a mysterious and mesmerizing film experience. This version of the film seems to be aimed at the newer generation of film goers with the theme that its a video game world. As someone who wishes this film to do well enough on its own merits, its absolutely night and day from the original. From the intriguing board game that captured your imagination, to the thrilling sense of danger in the set pieces, the humor, the sense of horror, the acting and amazing cast, the subtle yet poignant message at the end, and of course Robin Williams. The ONLY thing these two have in common is the name (aside from the newer film's caption). I'm just tired of these "Me Too" ideas coming from film studios with remakes that are based on either cult or mainstream classics. That and they are just scared of making something original.

text: I don't get the massive hate.  This version of Jumanji shows the other side of the Spectrum: what it is like to be inside the game, what Adam Parrish could've gone through when he was in it for 30-ish years (I think 33?). Which, for me, is interesting.   What I do not get though is how the hell Jumanji is a video game now? Couldn't they just made it so that the -ORIGINAL BOARD GAME- fell into the hands of a quartet of players, they play and THEY get sucked in the game, and then they must figure out how to get out?   The ''Video Game, choose your character, get sucked into the game and become that character'' could've been used for another plot in another movie.

text: They've replaced a story about a boy becoming a man with teenagers questioning social norms and becoming uncomfortable/comfortable in other people's skins. They've replaced a board game with a videogame. They've replaced a well-known single lead role with multiple well known lead roles. Jumanji always used CGI, Jumanji always had comedy, and even though I don't blame people who aren't interested in this; it's hard to tell if it's the movie that's formatted like a comedy or if it's today's marketing techniques that makes it look constantly ridiculous. It's not true to the original by any means but it is a proper remake in the sense that it takes the concept of Jumanji and gives it a twist. Not saying this movie will be great, but it is much more like the original than people are giving it credit for.

text: I genuinely cannot believe the reactions this is getting.   Fine, I understand that you guys don't like how your seemingly favourite movie from when you were a kid, Jumanji, has its name being used in an unrelated premise. However, that being said, this isn't completely far off from the Jumanji source material.   Unlike most people, my exposure to jumanji was from the TV show where the kids would get sucked into Jumanji - a jungle - where they would embark on a new adventure with a stuck Alan every episode. This is completely in line with the concept being shown here with the exception of the avatars. However, in the tv show, peter was sometimes turned into an animal, so take that as it is. This movie seems to be taking the concept introduced in the TV show and putting a modern spin on it by turning it into a video game.   Yes, using Jumanji to do this instead of making a standalone movie with the same premise was absolutely not necessary, but they probably owned the rights to this franchise and wanted to make more money. Movie studios being businesses, you should understand why they did it. Now, with that out of the way, do you still dislike the movie for what it is outside of Jumanji?   This trailer gives the vibe of a super fun movie! The cast is a good one for a comedy action film and the premise is decent. Why can't you see the movie for what it is/has the potential to be instead of grumbling about the usage of the Jumanji name. Like I pointed out, it's not /completely/ out of place using the Jumanji name and the trailer shows real promise.  I'm not entirely sure why I wrote this  whole out lol, but I just felt this movie needed to be cut a bit more slack considering how fun this looked to me.

See, if they watch these movies, they'' want to see the old ones too."  So I started thinking about it.  It is true, no matter how terrible remakes are, they can't really replace the old ones.  So that's not the problem.  It's a stilly argument in the day and age of massive streaming sites to claim that we're introducing an old movie by way of a crappy remake, when you could just...  Watch the original.  So that holds no weight, either.  And as for originality in movies, when we actually get originality it doesn't do so well...  True originality takes movies in new directions, directions that make simple-minded masses feel stupid, so they don't want to watch them.  So that's not going to work either.  But I finally figured out why GHOSTBUSTERS pisses me (and perhaps you, and perhaps everyone pissed off at this trailer) makes me so irritated.  It has nothing to do with the quality of this movie.  It has to do with THEFT.  The only way you can make a semi-okay remake of JUMANJI is if JUMANJI: 1.  Existed in the first place, planting the memory of it in our minds, and  2.  Was enough of a success for the mindless masses to remember it as well as those of us who ACTUALLY remember it, with fondness. We're angry because they're taking the original idea, and shitting all over it.  We're angry because they're taking something we enjoyed, and using it to rake in fake money, fake profits not based on the quality of the remake, but based on the suckering of the masses.  They don't have to make a good movie, and they know it, so why should they bother?  They're not doing this to improve an old idea, or "introduce it to a new generation" -- they're trying to cash in on our collective stupidity.    And the saddest part, my friends -- IT'S WORKING.  If the trailer makes you sick (like the FLATLINERS trailer looks to me as well) all you have to do is stand up to the fools that comment "you don't know if it will be bad if you haven't seen it".  "It could be just as good as the original, or even better!"  "You should give it a chance."  You should give it a chance...  Where have I heard that nonsense before...?  OH WAIT  [Just say NO to bad movies]

I genuinely want to see Jack Black (although he isn't my favourite actor I don't mind) whining like a pretty prep girl. The personalities for the bodies they have look pretty great. Be honest people, what teen in high school now a days would look at a board game and say "hey a cool board game, we have to play this!!" Vs "hey a retro game system, I wonder what nostalgic game it plays?" The board game suited the nineties because it was an ancient way to play. For this generation the old way to play games is game systems. I see it as the curse saw that kids weren't playing with a board game so it transformed into something more appealing and decided to pull the players in versus letting whatever was inside out. This concept makes it original but still tied to Jumanji in an updated way

text: This looks like it'll be a decent enough action movie with some comedy elements, but getting sucked into a video game gives more of a Spy Kids vibe than a Jumanji one. Now, they don't necessarily NEED a board game to make a Jumanji sequel work, but using a video game just seems off. Jumanji was about a game coming to life and invading the real world, not kids getting sucked into a video game and trying to get out. The latter idea has been used to the point of almost being cliche, but the former is a large part of what made Jumanji stand out. The distinction is subtle but has a big impact on the severity of the events that unfold in the story. Again I will say that it seems like it could be a pretty enjoyable movie if it's taken as a standalone experience with no association to the Jumanji brand. The problem is...they USED the Jumanji brand, so comparisons are going to abound. In fact, it seems like "just another action comedy movie" that is attempting to ride the coattails of a classic film, which is never a good impression to give off to your audience. In the end it will most likely annoy long time fans, NOT because of the movie itself, but rather because the sequel to a beloved and creative classic film is going to most likely be a by-the-numbers, okay action movie.

text: So yes I understand why some of you would be mad about this. I was too very skeptical sense I love the original so much. Those of you trying to compare this to Ghostbusters......STOP. Here's the difference. This is a continuation of the story bringing new ideas and NOT trying to do what the original did. Ghostbusters was literally a flat out reboot. This actually shows us what's inside the jungle and also bring new and clever ideas like the game being a old video game. But yes, this doesn't come without it's flaws. So far from what I've seen I was hoping for that kinda creepy or little bit more adventurous tone the original had. I remember the beginning freaking me out when I was young, getting sucked into a game. While there's stuff like that in this new version I don't see, I will still give this a chance. Whether you like the cast or not I think most of the cast is pretty great and can bring something new to the table if done right

text: This looks god awful. I mean,  they're digging around in the basement of a school. And they dont find an old board game? Really? WTF. They find a dusty old Atari? Real original. Do you hear the drums when you power up the console? LOL. Who made the game? Are there other copies? I guess we can forget about finding out about any lore or history to the original...What a cheap and lazy way of going about this film. And What was with the main character getting chewed up by a hippo at the end of the trailer? Is she going to survive that?  Was that a friendly hippo? Or did we see her die in the trailer? I remember Jumanji having a slightly more serious feel when it came to wild jungle animals. Now it just looks like generic explosions, upside down helicopter stunts, and recycled Kevin hart jokes. Name this anything else, but it's NOT Jumanji.

text: I saw the original as a kid. I'm honestly intrigued by this remake, reboot, re-imagining or whatever it's called. I think the key to a good remake isn't to re-do the movie shot for shot with the same actors, et cetera. What's the point of that? Just go watch the original if that's what you're after. I think a good remake needs to take the good ideas and themes from the original ( a dusty old game with magic powers that brings the jungle to the players and also brings the players into the game), and uses those ideas as a starting point for new ideas, new stories, new characters.  The ORIGINAL Mummy movie and the Brendan Fraiser Mummy are nothing alike, but people love both for different reasons. The "remake" of the Brendan Fraiser Mummy tries too hard to BE the Brendan Fraiser Mummy, and it really falls flat as a result. The 2016 Ghostbusters was trying too hard to be the "new" ghostbusters movie, rather than be a separate ghost busters movie that doesn't try to tread over the original. I think this Jumanji has potential to do it's own thing while keeping the original themes in tact.

text: Guys, the issue isn't that the movie doesn't look good. I laughed watching the trailer and thought it looked good! There's a big elephant in the room, though. It looks good for a basic 'game suck you in' type movie that ISN'T related to Jumanji. Part of the great part of Jumanji was feeling the emotions of Williams finding out his parents were dead and who he was didn't really exist anymore. It was scary, fun, funny, and even magical. This is just pure crazy humor. Which is FINE. But sony using the name 'Jumanji' shows their pure lazy and wanted to reap the benefits of the name. If you're not going to try and do the original at least HALF a bit of justice, don't use the name.

text: I will start by saying I adore the original Jumanji. Robin Williams is the main reason why. I also understand that this does not erase, negate, or insult the original movie. The original Jumanji will always be there.  I plan to actually see this before I whine, complain, and knock the movie. And unlike the uncivilized heathens that got so insulted over the Ghost Busters remake(which actually was funny and entertaining), I don't plan to insult and bully the actors if I don't like it.  P.S. If you don't like the idea of the Jumanji remake, buy dvd's/bluerays of the original. Stream it on netflix. Show you still love the old one. After that, you can either see the new movie and then decide if you don't like it. Or you can go on without watching it and possibly miss out on something fun.

text: One thing I hate about remakes are the fact that in the process of creating the original a lot of effort and creativity is put forth to ensure the targeted audience are left with quality. The story line must be memorable and picture perfect, and the cast members are scrutinized carefully to accurately illustrate the characters in the plot. Once that standard has been met, the film is then lifted to the heightened status of becoming a "classic" and all of the producers and actors are congratulated and awarded for such an amazing and historical project. Everyone goes home and celebrates their accomplishment as their name and film goes down in history. Remakes on the other hand lack all of these characteristics. Remake films remind me of fast food. They are only in it for the profit and care less about quality. In the case of Jumanji, this is a home cooked meal prepared with fresh organic groceries with the meat being tenderized over night, being re-made into a five dollar number 3 combo with extra salt and ketchup packets.

text: This movie will do OK. Just OK. I guess that's all Hollywood strives for anymore. It looks enjoyable with a fun and charismatic cast, but making it a part of the Jumanji franchise is an obvious money grab. Lazy, really. This trailer literally has nothing to do with Jumanji other than the name. The original Jumanji was from a time before they started dumbing down movies and turning them into what are essentially cartoons with real people. Dear Hollywood, stop trying to compete for the most teenagers and tell a decent story for a change. Don't get me wrong, I'll end up watching this movie, but I don't feel compelled to see it in theaters. I've seen enough of the cartoony, teenager-centric movies to know it won't be worth the cost of admission. Seen one, seen 'em all.

text: I'm actually confused because I thought the Jumanji board game was some kind of Native American voodoo magic. Now it's a video game. This means that there has to be an explanation as to who created it. With the original Jumanji the whole premise was that the board game changed the world around them. Now it's going to be 4 strangers get sucked into another world and have to work together get out (Fant4stic much?). I honestly think it's cliched. If they wanted for it to sell to younger children, then they could've still made the board game but have it in a 2017 context (Nobody even uses brick video game systems anymore either. Could've been a mobile phone game or whatever people play on these days). This honestly looks like a reverse Pixels. Also the lines, "You pick a character, and you're that person in the game" "I think we got sucked into Jumanji..." "This is a video game... which means we have special skills" That seems like poor writing to me. It's so obvious, you don't need to tell us that.

text: A good idea for a movie. It's got highly respected A-list actors playing as whiney teenagers as avatars in video game. That's funny and creative enough. The production unfortunately, I feel, has poor decision written all over it. First, the title says Jumanji. This would have been better as a sequel, like Zathura. Just marketing wise. Another issue I have is the casting; It's awful. The two nerdy white kids get to be smoking hot. And the mean girl is fat shamed, and stripped of her femininity. And the black kid is still black, only shorter.  This has to stop. It's not about lack of creativity anymore. Filmmakers are very creative. It's about presentation and representation. We're still whitewashing. We're still body shaming. We're still sexist. And. We're. Still. Racist. Stop this now. PLEASE.

text: I think when you're re-doing a franchise that was so iconic to a previous generation you can never win. Some will say it's too similar, others that it is not different enough. I like the premise of this film, it plays off the idea of movie character stereotypes while also evolving the idea of what Jumanji can be. Unlike the Ghostbusters rehash which just took the original film and swapped the cast with women, masquerading as progressive filmmaking, all with a hint of sexist overtone. I like this trailer, I think it's new, it's a cool idea and it transitions the concept of a game in which you are trapped to a new generation. If this film turns out to be good (which I hope it does) then great, but if not, we still have the original. I am optimistically looking forward to this film.

text: This movie would no doubt have been great if it had another title, but from what I'm seeing slapping Jumanji on it just seems like a cash grab to be honest. " In the jungle you must wait, until the dice read 5, or 8" The way Alan Parrish described the jungle of Jumanji once he was freed, it was a hellish place with creatures and scenes indescribable, with horrors that would eat you alive. I'm seeing none of that here. It wouldn't be so bad if they did their own take on things and it was given it's own name like "Zathura". The fact that they Jumped at the name Jumanji and changed a board game into a digital one perplexes me, and I give little care as to their explanation of why. Before anyone gets butthurt, that's my personal opinion. =/

text: The tone of the movie doesint even come close to its original. the og Jumanji was about 4 ppl who had a hard time in life dealing with major issues. Alan Parrish: dealing with getting stuck in the game and alot of time went by. his argument with his dad and the last thing he said to him was that he never wanted to see him again. when he finally was released the house was abandoned and finding out that his dad went insane spending everything he had trying find him. Sarah Whittle: getting involved into playing Jumanji by Alan and being the only person to seeing him get sucked into the game and all the unbelivable things that it did. on the night of Alan's dissapearence no one believed her. they made her go through mental ivaluation to see if she is crazy. she's the only one that knew what happen to alan but it made her go crazy that no one believed her. Peter and Judy Shepherd: dealing witht he lost of there parents. Judy was sarcastic and rebelious while Peter became distant and silent never to speak to anyone.  The game brought all of them together to deal with there there issues and to finally get over them. yeah its a comedy but its also has some sierious dramatic issues involved. thats what makes the original Jumanji fantastic. its wasint just stupid one liners and brain dead comedy.

text: First of all, I have to give props to the filmmakers for taking the concept of Jumanji, updating it, and taking it into a new direction. I like the idea that it doesn't try to capture the spirit of the old movie, mainly because, well, it's been done.   Granted, I miss the emotional and serious tone of the original. This movie seems like it's aiming for comedy and action, but with that said, it does seem like they've gotten a fairly likable cast to give it all a fair degree of charm. I like the idea of teenagers turned into the equivalents of Cluedo characters that are mismatched with their actual personalities, I like the idea of rather than just bringing Jumanji to them, they're brought to Jumanji, and I really like that it kind of begins like a Cabin in the Woods storyline, with teenagers finding the game in the cellar.  Only real issue I have is this: Why did it have to be teenagers? Why is it ALWAYS teenagers? They're at a school, why didn't they use actual kids for main characters for once? The idea of a preteen boy in The Rock's body is way funnier than what I guess is the geek who will save the day.

text: You know what, I can completely disregard the fact that an adaptation has nothing to do with its source material if it's a good movie. This just looks like a really shitty, stupid movie. People getting sucked into a video game is a dated premise, and I think that getting different, more popular actors playing the kids when they're sucked in is just an easy way to bring in the box office dollars. You could have had the same actors get sucked into the game and it would not only make the story make a lot more sense that way, but it would also make it look like you didn't feel you had to try so hard.

text: I like the Rock but I like him as a person, I don't really get excited for any of his movies, I like Jack Black too and he's made some ace stuff but what has he done recently that has been noteworthy? Kevin Hart is like a black Will Ferrell to some extent, he is shorter but still loves making manic and loud noises whilst screaming, and therefore i'm not really into him and still don't understand the hype around him. Then there's Karen Gillan, she's pretty decent but not like outstanding, haven't seen her in as much stuff recently other than GOTG, which she is arite in I guess (enjoyed her in Doctor Who) but then again seeing her in this role just looks meh. The film could be funny but at the same time it also looks very, very underwhelming and has lost its charm that the original had by modernising it so much that it will probably be cringey.   TO BE HONEST WITH YOU THOUGH...  What I really wanna see is a hard R rated Jumanji, where people get fucked up and it acts almost like a horror movie. I watched the original again recently and it was genuinely a bit scary at times with enough lightheartedness to it to (I guess) make it a childrens film. Obviously make it a Horror Comedy like Evil Dead 2 because the premise is a little too ridiculous to take seriously but you could get some genuine good scares in. Did no one else find the beating drums a bit eerie and creepy when they got played in the original? Imagine some sort of creature or plant monster stalking them whilst that music was playing, it would be waaaaaaaaay intense. Then imagine the total grizzly deaths by some of the creatures in the film.  Just an idea that no one will probably read or like because I wasn't super positive about The Rock, Kevin Hart, Jack Black and I guess Karen Gillan (3 of whom I actually like) but oh well, just throwing it out there (:

text: So this is actually a sequel and not a remake. They got rid of the board game aspect and it is now a video game. A probably explanation is that some kids played the game in the 90s and destroyed it after completing it. Once they destroyed it, the spirit or whatever in the video game was transferred to the nearby video game console. However, this doesn't explain how the game suddenly created 4 different characters with different personalities.This to me is just an excuse to have Dwayne Johnson and Kevin Hart in the same film (again), while keeping the whole "kids playing the game" aspect. To me, this is just an obvious cash grab film. It appeals to the younger generation (probably going to be rated PG like the first one) and draws the attention of the older generation because it has the name Jumanji. We'll see if it's good, but for now I'm not happy with this.

If it was considered a spin-off, which the title kinda makes it sound like, you should be fine. It's not re-doing the same film, it's not saying it's as good, it's just an option for those who want to see an all-star cast take on a twist on the Jumanji story-line.

If it's a *genuine problem*, like you don't find it funny, or you feel like the whole video game concept is a shark-jumping cash grab, then I respect your opinion (as long as you don't shove it down my throat), then I respect you and your opinion. If you're just blindly hating it because it's a sequel, made past year/creation x, or both, then I kindly ask you to banish yourself to that part of the internet that reverently worships your "utopian time period" that doesn't exist, and let the mature people calmly  discuss their opinions. text: I think if they absolutely wanted to do another Jumanji movie, they should have done a sequel rather than what I assume is a reboot. This doesn't seem to be anything like the Robin Williams one, and while I hate it when a studio is trying to cash in on childhood nostalgia, this just seem not to try at all as the only thing the two movies really seem to have in common is the title.  I don't know why Sony has made it their mission to make flatter versions of classic movies, as one would have thought they would learn something after the 2016 Ghostbusters. While I've personally always wanted to see the world within the game explored, this doesn't do it for me at all as it seems to lack the feeling of the original product, which had a very bittersweet tone and likable characters with depth.  The game isn't even done right. Why couldn't they just bring back the board game from the original and call it a sequel? Is it because Sony thought that children were too stupid to find interest in a movie about a magic board games? Because I think is.  Jack Black, Kevin Hart and the Rock are all very intertaining actors, but they only seem to be in this to bring their fanbases to cinemas rather than bringing something unique to this and building on the story.  Overall, this story doesn't even need to be called Jumanji or associated with that franchise as it obviously doesn't seem to have anything in common with the Robin Williams movie. Actually, you could slap a Jurassic Park, King Kong or The Breakfast club title on this movie and it would seem more faithful to those movies than this.

text: Pretty much all of these characters look like stereotypes. The nerdy protagonist, the big black jock, the shy school girl, the hot and pretty girl. It's like no one in Hollywood is trying to make a film that they'd like to watch but are instead just pulling stuff out of their butt. Also it looks really boring. In the original we never got to see the world but it was made to seem like a nightmare by how relieved Alan was after leaving the board game, and how the two boys who buried it in the beginning ran scared. The people in the original didn't want to play because every time it was someone's turn they knew something bad was gonna attack them like bats, or giant spiders, or killer plants, or a huge stampede of animals. The jungle is no where near as cool or terrifying as our imaginations made it out to be because the people making this movie had no imagination.

text: OK, I'll admit, at the risk of being beheaded by the haters, it doesn't look that bad. Granted, I'm still betting my life savings that the original will stand high and tall against this movie, and I'm probably not going to go see it in theaters, but it looks like stupid, actually enjoyable (briefly, at the very least, maybe 2-3 cool moments max) action schlock.  My biggest complaint is, you manage to make a movie's concept getting literally sucked into a video game, AND YOU MAKE IT A FREAKIN' REBOOT OF JUMANJI!?! WHY!?! There are SO many missed opportunities to use that setup for something way more awesome and won't get severe backlash from fans! Killer aliens, giant robots, mushroom land, the list goes on with the things that you could've done that wouldn't have pissed people off.  Also, I swear to crap, if there's a scene where Rock and Black make out because Black's a girl, I might just stab my eyes out.

text: I think the main reason this trailer makes me uncomfortable is because it's such a drastic change from the original.  Not just because high school and video game, but because it looks like it's going to be more about action than survival. By giving the characters "skills" they become empowered, and this takes away suspense from the film, suspense that can only be recovered by spending tons of money on action and spectacle.  I'm worried that indulgence in that spectacle will make the filmmakers lose sight of the original's spirit and heart.

text: The structure of the original film was so clever, with their rolling of the dice on a board game affecting their actual world, and providing a means of well thought out pacing, and story development. In that regard, it can at least be said, that this movie is not a total rip-off.  Hollywood has never been universally creative, but ever since stealing movies and music became not only easy, but acceptable, no effort has been put into either medium. "Kids won't understand what a boardgame is today, better make it a videogame."  Well, the kids in the first film weren't exactly fans of board games either,  that allowed for development of a more nuanced plot (which the original film didn't have to begin with. It wasn't even that great of a movie, but this preview makes it look brilliant by comparison.)   These characters are all the same one-dimensional high school stereotypes we've seen in every other crappy film. The industry is just snapping up franchises, and applying the aesthetics of the former to the same characters, and the same story as every other pile of bile that gets regurgitated out of the collective Hollywood gut, hoping that something will stick. But only one thing sticks in such a scenario.

text: Gee, the lack of humility before the orginal Jumanji, that's being displayed here, uh... staggers me. Don't you see the stupidity, inherent in what you're doing here? Making a sequel/reboot/sequeal reboot is the most awesome force people ever seen, but you wield it like a kid that's found his dad's gun. If I may... Um, I'll tell you the problem with the cinematic power that you're using here, it didn't require any discipline to attain it. You watched what others had done and you took the next step. You didn't earn the original movie for yourselves, so you don't take any responsibility for it. You stood on the shoulders of geniuses to accomplish something as fast as you could, and before you even knew what you had, you patented it, and packaged it, and slapped it into theatres. Your producers, directors, and writers were so preoccupied with whether or not they could, that they didn't stop to think if they should.

text: *This is why Jumanji will fail*  *The original film had comedian Robin Williams in it, by it was by no means a comedy. It was a rather dark film in tonality, whilst dealing with serious issues such as loss of innocence, alienation, fear, mortality, and survivalist themes. It was by no means a horror film, but issues were significant at hand.*  *You actually felt for Alan, Sarah, Judy and Peter; and rather symbolic that Alan, Judy, and Peter's parents are dead, or the utter genius symbolism of having Van Pelt mirror Samuel Parrish (an aspect used in J. M. Barrie's Peter Pan) as Alan nemesis within Jumanji for twenty-six years. With the characters in this reboot, I'm 100% certain you won't get the emotional attachment or development you saw in Joe Johnston's Jumanji.*  *This film is simply seems like just a great waste of what could have been; a film taking part within the events of the twenty-six years in which Alan was stuck within Jumanji, a sequel containing an older Judy and Peter? One fusing the events of Jumanji and Zathura in answering the question who created the games, but most importantly why?*

text: Sigh :(. Jumanji is a cursed object that unleashes a world of horror that tries to murder you, or worse. Only if you manage to finish the game, do you get to live. Jumanji is not Oculus Rift.  There is no tension, no fear, no terror, no horror in this remake. It's just a has been and a bunch of never was hamming in front of a green screen displaying a boring shooter video game.  The characters are too old to seem endangered, and their even older avatars only make it worse. They're not even friends, let alone family, so there is no possibility of dramatic tension. They aren't even really characters, as they have no unique personality, they are just bare archetypes (the popular girl, the unpopular girl, the black boy, the Jewish boy).  The plot can be seen a kilometer away! They will fail and fail and whine and whine until they realise they each have a video game superskill. They will use their superskills badly, barely managing to survive, until the "last battle" where they finally learn to use them competently. Once back in reality, they will find that the video game "skill" they learned helps them in real life.  I predict this film will be just a string of loud explosions and flashing lights, occasionally broken by infantile dialog posing as "jokes". It will be yet another "group of antisocial ciphers with nothing in common will learn to work together as a team to defeat a great evil" style story. I'm honestly shocked that JJ Abrams didn't write the screenplay.

text: I am a huge fan of the original Jumanji. People are immediately comparing this movie to the female  Ghostbusters movie, but while that movie was basically a complete copy of the original Ghostbusters, the new Jumanji takes a very different approach to the game by turning the teens into videogame characters which I think is the main point of comedy. Everyone's pissed about Jumanji not being a board game, but I think it being a videogame makes it more relatable to the present time. I also love the comedic charisma of Jack Black, Kevin Heart, and The Rock. Again, I love the original Jumanji and Robin Williams will always remain a legendary actor and comedian, but I do think this movie looks hilarious and I can't wait to see it.

text: So many people complaining about how "disgraceful" this is to Robin Williams. How? He didn't make the movie nor did he own the rights to it. He was just in it. Is it then disgraceful to Kirsten Dunst too? Or is it only considered "disgraceful" after a person dies? Secondly, you haven't even seen the bloody movie yet. I won't lie, I have pretty low expectations but it's silly to just assume it's definitely gonna be a bad film because there's no Robin Williams. Also, don't let nostalgia blind you into thinking the original Jumanji was a masterpiece. Yes, it was one of my favourite childhood adventures but it is certainly no Jurassic Park. Watching it again as a critical thinking adult, I couldn't ignore the thin plot, bad CGI (even by 1995 standards) and overall cheesiness. It's actually kind of a mess and if it were released now, it would probably receive mostly negative reviews. Zathura was a stronger film and this might be too.

It was an adventure drama with some comedic moments but there was legit terror in it, mosquitos that could kill you, man eating plants, man hunting british guy, floods, stampedes, nasty bugs... and real stakes and danger of being killed horrendously. text: not bad, if this is seen as an alternate reality from the other movie, and that Jumanji was not created till the 1980's rather than some time during or before the 19th century; however, what is under everyone skin is the fact that the premise of Jumanji has changed. Jumanji in itself was an cursed game, that brought peril to the player itself, in their present day and surroundings, each being original and not pre-set. Robin Williams (Alan) was uniquely cursed into going inside a jungle. To say that would happen again would be uncertain and doubtful. text: Now look I'm going to say this once and once only. Everybody in the comments defending this as a jumanji movie...stop. There is no way your winning over anyone. Straight up this movie fails as a sequel to jumanji. Making it into a video game doesn't make it relatable it just makes it a lame idea that has been done before (TRON). What made jumanji work was you as an every day person had to survive. You never had any "special abilities" or advantages. Making it into a video game is a huge blow to fans and thats not going to heal so sorry for people trying to give this film a chance as a jumanji movie. Now for the people defending this as a movie in general I can understand. If they didn't just blindly slap jumanji to this film that I would probably find it actually enjoyable sum what. It has grate actors that I enjoy and love seeing and I love to see what they half to offer. In the end this movie sucks ONLY as a jumanji movie no if ands or buts or trying to defend it as part of the franchise it fails as a sequel to the original period

text: Everyone is saying that this is just a remake. When, it's really not. Dwayne Johnson said that the film is a sequel to the original, and a tribute to Robin Williams. Plus, it's something different. If it was a shot for shot remake of the original film, you would all still be butthurt about the fact that it ruins the original, which is a good movie, but not a masterpiece. It's fun of course, but it doesn't hold up the best over time. Besides, this film gives us a look into the world of Jumanji for the first time in live action. It's something different, and it looks fun and entertaining.

text: Look... I'm not saying this is automatically a bad movie, but it ain't fuckin' Jumanji, okay?! Call it something else, and make an actual good remake of Jumanji with tighter writing, updated (less cliche) plot elements, and better effects. Don't saddle us with this bullshit and call it Jumanji, just call it "Welcome to the Jungle" and we're good. Or hell, they could've kept the Jumanji name and had a bunch of kids somehow find the game board after it was washed up by the river. That'd mean it would tie in nicely with the previous movie, keep the audience nostalgic for it, and make younger kids interested in the old movie. Triple-whammy of monetary success there.

text: Watched this in the cinema today and here's my honest opinion of it. While there were a few moments of genuine laughter, I felt myself cringing at a lot of this movie. The villain doesn't have much to offer into the films story and when he does crop up it's nothing too thrilling. For a Jumanji sequel, it felt more like a cross between Jurassic Park and Indiana Jones. It felt as if the movie wasn't sure wether it wanted to be a comedy or an action and due to this fell short in some areas, leaving it feeling flat at times. As much as I like the rock I grew tired of the self admiration he had towards his own character at times throughout the movie. Overall would probably be a 5/10.

text: I watched this already early screening for VIP here's the summary SPOILERS: Spencer, Flinch, Martha and Bethany are all opposites of each other and get detention for some reason. Flinch finds a game and they alll choose an avatar and gets stuck in it. Each person has strengths and weaknesses they have three lines on their arm which represents their life. A character from the game picks them up with a car and explains the rules that jumanji is in danger and only way to escape is by returning the jaguars jewel which he miraculously had. Before getting to the jaguars statue they must go through levels and they get a map to help them. A piece is missing so they look for it but instead of a paper the missing piece was Nick Jonas or Alex as he is the fifth player. He doesn't realise he's been stuck there for 20 years as they return they are faced challenges by the guy who took the jaguars stone. By doing so he gained powers of controlling animals and gets jumanji cursed and they save jumanji eventually and become really good friends sounds meh but funniest movie ever love it!!!!

text: Video was too long. Halfway through it, I got hungry so I left it playing and went to the kitchen to fix myself a sandwich. But then I found out that I'm out of mayonnaise so I went to the store to get some. There, I saw the most beautiful woman I have ever seen in my whole life. But I'm really a shy person so I took up a three-year personality development course so I can introduce my self. She was very friendly and all, but unfortunately, she has a boyfriend. So I said, all good, I'm a mature person. I want the best for her and I harbor no illusion that I am the best person for her and she seems happy with her boyfriend, so I did not bother her anymore. But we kept in touch and we became friends and I got over my crush on her. Then she broke up with her boyfriend, we drank some alcohol because of it, I told her she'll be fine and I wished her well. I still think she's the most beautiful woman in the world, but like I said, I am over my crush on her. It was like five years already when I first saw her. Besides, I am quite happy with the friendship I developed with her. It was more important than a crush. So we kept hanging out, drinking, having coffee, and all. I had a girlfriend, she started dating other guys. My girlfriend wants to live some other life without me in it, so I said, okay, I want the best for you and I want you to pursue your happiness. My lady friend and I drank alcohol about it, and she gave me the same advice I gave her when she was in that position and I became okay with the breakup immediately. But we were really drunk, so she spent the night in my apartment. I only have one bed, so you know what that means: She took the bed and I slept on the couch. But on the couch, I really can't sleep. Something was bothering me. So I tossed and turned for about three hours, then I finally can't take it anymore, I stood up and went straight to my room where she's sleeping. I approached the bed, gently sat on it and I reached for her shoulder to pull her closer to me. She stirred and woke up. She asked what's up. I told her, you know, the first time I saw you, I was watching a video and left it playing to get my self a sandwich then went to the store to get some mayo then I got distracted by life that I forgot to finish the video. She said, you know what, I've been wondering about a weird noise in your night drawer. So we opened that drawer, and lo and behold, there's my phone  and this video still had four minutes of play time on it.

text: Iâ€™ll admit, I was extremely skeptical about this movie as well, but after seeing it, I thoroughly enjoyed it. Iâ€™ll do a quick rundown of the difference on the scenarios and why they are like that (I wonâ€™t spoil anything that doesnâ€™t happen within the first 10 minutes). It starts in 1996 when a father brings his teenage son after finding it buried, (presumably after the events of the original), when the son looks at it but doesnâ€™t play it on account it is a board game to play video games instead, the game changes its form overnight to suit his desires, then he plays and gets sucked in like the original, the key difference in this is that when other people later find it, instead of them sucking the game into their world, it sucks them into it. Yes it does use video game logic and it makes up some of the best scenes in the movie, all and all it was actually incredibly entertaining, and doesnâ€™t discredit the original in my opinion.

text: Saw the movie twice, and was quite fond of it. It even managed to smoothen out some of the originals flaws:  - A more structured, less random storyline. - Dedicated villain, instead of "random dude walzing by and drops in the last few minutes as we needed someone for a showdown". - Player Avatar with different abilities showed the aspect of persons becoming "playing pieces".  The action scenes (even as this trailer indicates otherwise) were usually not random mayhem, but had a story/joke to tell. E.g. we see Karen Gillian/Ruby Roundhouse kicking two Goons to the ground in the trailer...we didn't see the minutes before were she (without any success) tried to seduce those guards in the most incompetent, hilarious way (the whole movie theatre was roaring with laughter).  All in all: While not eligible to win an Oscar, the new Jumanjii is a very nicely done action comedy, providing laugher at pleasantly short intervals.

text: I get that they changed Jumanji into a video game for the newer generation and because no one would play board games in modern times  But let's be real - bringing back the board game concept would have worked since Jumanji is a not so normal board game that produces sound when kids are near it. Modern day us would have not ignored it. There you start with a group of kids, some find the board game and thinks it would be boring, and a curious kid will try to play it. The pieces then stick to the board, other kids will think it's some sort of modern contraption, and will continue to play. They will think maybe the creatures coming out is a hologram until the game proves them wrong. And I thought this all up in just 5 mins. There are other creative ways to make the board game work. What about a family trip? Maybe they were camping, so no wifi. Maybe it was Thanksgiving, and an Aunt insisted on playing a board game she found in an antique shop.  I understand this is a remake but the concept of Jumanji being a board game is unique to itself, that is why a lot of people loved it. I just wish they retained it.

text: The game always finds a way. And it does in this long awaited sequel yes, itâ€™s a sequel to the blockbuster hit jumanji. This second installment of the franchise stars Dwayne Johnson, Jack Black And Kevin Hart you could not of asked for a better trio. They are hilarious together Jack Black does an excellent job at playing the popular pretty teenage blonde girl. He was perfect for that role. The actors did such a great job playing their teenage counterparts. And one thing I loved the characters grew. I wonâ€™t go into any further detail no spoilers here. The story was very good as well and the director was great to. The movie is hilarious it had me laughing from start to finish. I actually was worried about this but they nailed it Robin Williams would be proud. This is a great movie. And to see Kevin Hart slap The Rock was pure comedy gold. If you have not seen this movie then I recommend you do oh and Karen Gillan who played Ruby Roundhouse was good as well. This movie is cinematastic rating 5/5

text: You call that a Sequel?  Jumanji 2: Into the Jungle Release date: December 19th 1997 Director: Joe Johnson Composer (Very Important): James Horner ðŸ˜­ RIP. Cast: Robin WilliamsÂ as Alan Parrish  Kirsten DunstÂ as Judith Shepherd  Bradley PierceÂ as Peter Shepherd  David Alan GrierÂ as Carl Bentley  Bonnie HuntÂ as Sarah Whittle  Jonathan HydeÂ as Van Pelt  Patricia ClarksonÂ as Carol-Anne Parrish  Malcolm StewartÂ as James Shepherd  Annabel KershawÂ as Martha Shepherd  Frank WelkerÂ provides the special vocal effects Based on the book by Chris Van Alsburg. Plot: Alan and the three main characters get sucked into the board game of Jumanji and must survive in order to reach the city of Jumanji. Distributed by: Tristar Picture.
